following management options would be most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Metoprolol","Ramipril","Propranolol","Pantoprazole","Terlipressin"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENon-selective beta-blockers are the current drug of choice for prevention of variceal bleeding. \u003Cstrong\u003EPropranolol \u003C/strong\u003Eis a noncardioselective beta-blocker and it works in reducing the risk of further variceal haemorrhage by lowering portal pressure through its action on the reduction of portal venous flow. Carvidolol competes with adrenergic neurotransmitters at sympathetic receptor sites. More recently carvedilol has been proposed as the noncardioselective beta-blocker of choice for patients with portal hypertension and oesophageal varices, but these benefits could be negated in patients with advanced decompensation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Emetoprolol\u003C/strong\u003E is also a beta-blocker, it is cardio-selective (B1 specific) and so does not confer benefit for prevention of variceal haemorrhage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETerlipressin\u003C/strong\u003E is a vasopressor analogue that has a role in the management of acute variceal haemorrhage through inducing splanchnic vasoconstriction. It is not appropriate for the longer term secondary prophylaxis of variceal bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPantoprazole\u003C/strong\u003E is used to prevent re-bleeding of peptic ulcers by reducing gastric acid secretion. It is not useful for long term management for reducing the risk of variceal bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERamipril\u003C/strong\u003E is a drug used for systemic essential hypertension. It is not used for portal hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Non-selective beta-blockers can provide effective secondary prophylaxis against variceal haemorrhage."],"references":["Kaplan DE, Ripoll C, Thiele M, Fortune BE, Simonetto DA, Garcia-Tsao G, et al. AASLD Practice Guidance on risk stratification and management of portal hypertension and varices in cirrhosis. Hepatology [Internet]. 2024;79(5). Available from: https://journals.lww.com/hep/fulltext/2024/05000/aasld_practice_guidance_on_risk_stratification_and.22.aspx","Villanueva C, Tripathi D. Carvedilol, probably the \u03b2-blocker of choice for everyone with cirrhosis and portal hypertension: But not so fast! Liver International. 2023; 43:1154\u201356."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38302"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1393"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38302","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38302"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-12T14:47:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-12T14:48:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1393"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52912"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical stud